    <body>
        <sect1>
            <title>Basic Combat</title>

            <para>
                This is a basic introduction to the <tm>Yags</tm>
                combat system, and a description of low tech fighting,
                using swords, bows and brawling. Modern day warfare
                is covered in <ref>Modern Combat</ref> and futuristic
                combat is covered in <ref>Future Combat</ref>.
            </para>

            <para>
                <note>It is assumed that the reader has read both the
                Introduction and the Character articles before reading
                this article.</note>
            </para>

            <sect2>
                <title>General Terminology</title>

                <para>
                    The following terms are used frequently within
                    these rules, so they are described up front. A
                    full description of how they are used will be
                    given later.
                </para>

                <termlist sort="true">
                    <entry term="Round">
                        A round is a unit of time, averaging
                        about five seconds. Each round, a
                        character has chance to perform a
                        single action - normally an attack or
                        a move. Five seconds is actually quite
                        a long time in a melee fight, so a fair
                        degree of latitude is allowed as regards
                        to what can be accomplished. However,
                        only a single attack may ever be made.
                    </entry>

                    <entry term="Body Levels">
                        Every creature has a number of body
                        levels, which represent their health.
                        Most creatures have a number of body
                        levels equal to their size plus two.
                        The extra two represent <s>OK</s>
                        and <s>Fatal</s> which are at
                        either extreme of a living creature's
                        state of health.
                    </entry>

                    <entry term="Soak">
                        Soak is how good a creature is at
                        resisting (soaking) damage. An adult
                        human will usually have a base soak of
                        12. Any armour worn adds to this.
                    </entry>

                    <entry term="Wounds">
                        Wounds are serious injuries which have
                        a good chance of causing death. They
                        often puncture the skin, resulting in
                        bleeding and possible the loss of vital
                        organs. A creature can suffer a number of wounds
                        equal to their body levels before dying.
                    </entry>

                    <entry term="Stuns">
                        Stuns are non-serious injuries which
                        result in bruises and pain. They will
                        rarely kill, but a severe beating can
                        in theory inflict enough stuns to kill
                        a person, since excessive stuns translate
                        into <s>wounds</s>. Once someone has stuns
                        equal to their body levels, they are practically
                        out of the fight.
                    </entry>
                    
                    <entry term="Fatigue">
                        Fatigue is a measure of how tired a creature is.
                        Unlike wounds and stuns, the amount of fatigue a
                        creature can handle is based on their stamina.
                        There are two types of fatigue - temporary and
                        permanent. Temporary fatigue is more common in
                        combat, and can be recovered with a short rest.
                        Permanent fatigue can only be recovered after a
                        good nights sleep, but is only gained through
                        sleep deprivation or after several hours of
                        physical effort.
                    </entry>

                    <entry term="Damage">
                        Damage is done when one creature hits
                        another. Often, damage induces wounds or
                        stuns in the target. An attack will
                        inflict either <term>wounds</term>,
                        <term>stuns</term> or <term>mixed</term>
                        damage which is split between stuns and
                        wounds. Many animals cause mixed damage
                        with claw and bite attacks.
                    </entry>

                    <entry term="Load">
                        A character's load is a measure of how
                        much they are carrying. Each weapon and
                        piece of armour has a load associated
                        with it. If the total load is greater
                        than the character's strength x 4, then
                        they are considered to be encumbered and
                        at penalty.
                    </entry>

                    <entry term="Special Attack">
                        A special attack is chosen before
                        initiative is determined, and can have
                        a modifier on how a character attacks,
                        and also on the results of the attack.
                        Individual special attacks are described
                        later, but include such things as killing
                        blow or aimed shot. They are very useful,
                        and players should be aware of their
                        options.
                    </entry>
                </termlist>
            </sect2>

            <sect2>
                <title>Fighting Styles</title>

                <para>
                    When a character or creature makes an attack,
                    they do so using one of a number of different
                    fighting styles. Each fighting style has its
                    own skill, and is independent of the weapon
                    being used.
                </para>

                <termlist>
                    <entry term="Brawling">
                        Brawling is the simplest style of fighting,
                        involving punching, kicking and grappling.
                        It also covers use of small weapons such
                        as a knife, dagger or broken bottle. Since
                        the skill of brawling is one of the eight
                        basic talents all people have, everyone has
                        some skill in it. Creatures generally use
                        brawling attacks.
                    </entry>

                    <entry term="Single weapon">
                        The single weapon fighting style involves using
                        a single one handed weapon to attack with. A
                        shield cannot be used. Most weapons, other than
                        shields and two handed weapons, can be used with
                        this style, and only a single skill (single weapon)
                        is needed to cover them all.
                    </entry>

                    <entry term="Weapon and shield">
                        This fighting style uses a combination of a one
                        handed weapon and a shield, to give what is
                        possibly the best combination. Any type of shield,
                        and any one handed weapon can be used with this
                        style.
                    </entry>

                    <entry term="Great weapon">
                        The great weapon style allows use of a single
                        weapon which requires two hands to use it. It
                        suffers from lack of defence, but such weapons
                        can be very good at cleaving through armour.
                    </entry>

                    <entry term="Two weapons">
                        This style of fighting involves the use of two one
                        handed weapons at once. Though this gives an edge
                        over only using one weapon, it does not grant two
                        attacks in a combat round. Further, it is
                        generally not as good as using a shield instead
                        of a second weapon, but it does have its advantages.
                    </entry>

                    <entry term="Longshaft weapon">
                        This style of fighting uses a single two handed
                        weapon such as a long spear, quarterstaff or
                        lance, or single handed versions of the same. A
                        shield may be used if the weapon is one handed.
                    </entry>
                    
                    <entry term="Flail weapon">
                        Flails are a small category of weapon which are
                        quite rare, consisting of a number of balls or
                        rods, attached via chain or leather to a haft.
                        They can be used with or without a shield. They
                        have the advantage that when used defensively,
                        the defence bonus is +10 (rather than +5). If
                        used aggresively, then the attack bonus is +10
                        (rather than +5). See the section on special
                        attacks for more information.
                    </entry>
                </termlist>
            </sect2>

            <sect2>
                <title>Combat Statistics</title>

                <para>
                    Each weapon has a number of statistics which
                    represents how effective it is. These give a bonus
                    to a character's skill checks in combat. All
                    bonuses are zero or positive - no weapon gives a
                    negative adjustment to combat actions.
                </para>

                <para>
                    Creatures which have natural attacks have their
                    own combat modifiers, depending on the nature of
                    their natural weapons. Generally, these are worse
                    than those of man made weapons. Size, reach and
                    sharpness all have a say in how effective natural
                    weapons are for a given type of creature.
                </para>

                <termlist>
                    <entry term="Initiative">
                        The initiative of a weapon represents how quickly
                        it can be brought to use. In a round, character's
                        with a high initiative act before those with lower
                        initiatives. Long weapons can grant a high
                        initiative since they provide a tactical advantage
                        for their user.
                    </entry>

                    <entry term="Attack">
                        The attack rating of a weapon gives a bonus to hit
                        a target. The attacker's attack skill is rolled
                        against the defender's defence skill.
                    </entry>

                    <entry term="Defence">
                        The defence rating of a weapon adds to a
                        characters parry or dodge attempts. Normally,
                        defence is dexterity based if the character is
                        using a melee weapon, or agility based if not.
                        The single weapon combat style allows the
                        character to choose whether to use agility or
                        dexterity for defence.
                    </entry>

                    <entry term="Damage">
                        The weapon damage adds to the strength of the
                        user, and is unaffected by skill.
                    </entry>
                </termlist>

            </sect2>

        </sect1>


        <sect1>
            <title>Weapons</title>

            <para>
                There are a variety of different weapons, all with their
                own advantages and disadvantages. The table lists the
                most common weapons, together with the statistics which
                are required in combat.
            </para>

            <import-weaponlist href="../equipment/weapons.xml"/>

            <para>
                The four ability modifiers - initiative, attack, defence and
                damage add to the base ability for a character when they are
                using that weapon.
            </para>

            <para>
                The given strength is the minimum strength required to use the
                weapon effectively. If this strength is not met, then the
                character is at -5 to initiative, attack and defence per point
                below. If the weapon is being used two handed, then add 50%
                (round up) to the character's strength for this purpose only.
            </para>

            <para>
                The weapon's load is a measure of how heavy it is. The load of
                all weapons, armour and equipment being carried needs to be
                totalled, and compared to the character's strength, to see if
                they are encumbered. More on this later.
            </para>

            <sect2>
                <title>Using Weapons in Combat</title>

                <para>
                    When engaging in combat, a character or creature
                    has five four main statistics which govern whether
                    the attack succeeds or fails. These are based on
                    the character's skill, with a modifier for the
                    weapon.
                </para>

                <skillequation>
                    <title>Initiative</title>
                    <attribute>agility</attribute>
                    <skill>skill</skill>
                    <bonus>weapon initiative bonus</bonus>
                    <die/>
                </skillequation>

                <skillequation><title>Brawl attack</title>
                    <attribute>agility</attribute>
                    <skill>skill</skill>
                    <bonus>weapon attack bonus</bonus>
                    <die/>
                </skillequation>

                <skillequation><title>Melee attack</title>
                    <attribute>dexterity</attribute>
                    <skill>skill</skill>
                    <bonus>weapon attack bonus</bonus>
                    <die/>
                </skillequation>

                <skillequation><title>Missile attack</title>
                    <attribute>perception</attribute>
                    <skill>skill</skill>
                    <bonus>weapon attack bonus</bonus>
                    <die/>
                </skillequation>

                <skillequation><title>Parry Defence</title>
                    <attribute>dexterity</attribute>
                    <skill>skill</skill>
                    <bonus>weapon defence bonus</bonus>
                    <die/>
                </skillequation>

                <skillequation><title>Brawl Defence</title>
                    <attribute>agility</attribute>
                    <skill>skill</skill>
                    <bonus>weapon defence bonus</bonus>
                    <die/>
                </skillequation>

                <skillequation><title>Weapon damage</title>
                    <attribute>strength</attribute>
                    <constant>4</constant>
                    <bonus>weapon damage bonus</bonus>
                    <die/>
                </skillequation>

                <para>
                    An axe for example has an initiative of +6. If
                    the character has a skill of 5 and an agility of
                    3, then their initiative is 5 &#215; 3 (15) + 6 = 21.
                </para>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Shields</title>

                    <para>
                        If a character is using a shield, then bonuses
                        from the shield are added to the bonuses of the
                        primary weapon. This can greatly bias combat in
                        favour of having a shield. Further, there are
                        other bonuses gained from using a shield when
                        fighting multiple opponents, which is described
                        later.
                    </para>
                </sect3>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Fighting with Two Weapons</title>

                    <para>
                        When fighting with two weapons, the weapon in
                        the off hand is the secondary weapon, and the
                        other weapon is considered the primary weapon.
                        Half the statistics (rounded down) of the
                        secondary weapon are added to those of the
                        primary weapon.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        Since both weapons give a bonus to damage,
                        this style of fighting has one advantage over
                        using a shield (which generally doesn't give
                        any damage bonuses). However, defending with two
                        weapons isn't as easy as defending with a weapon
                        and shield.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        The minimum strength requirement of the secondary
                        weapon is increased by two.
                    </para>
                </sect3>
            </sect2>
        </sect1>

        <sect1>
            <title>Melee Combat</title>

            <para>
                Strictly speaking, melee combat involves two or more
                characters fighting each other close up with melee
                weapons. The rules for melee combat form the basis
                of other forms of combat as well (such as ranged
                combat), so the basic rules of combat are
                described here.
            </para>

            <para>
                All combat is divided into rounds, and each round is
                broken into a number of different steps. Various book
                keeping activities happen at the end of each round.
            </para>

            <sect2>
                <title>The Combat Round</title>

                <para>
                    The sequence of events in each round is as follows.
                </para>

                <orderedlist type="1">
                    <item>
                        Determine character actions.
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        Roll initiative.
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        Perform actions in decreasing order of initiative.
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        End of round book keeping.
                    </item>
                </orderedlist>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Determine Actions</title>

                    <para>
                        The first step in each round involves
                        determining what each character or creature
                        is going to be doing. Since a round lasts
                        five seconds, there is generally time to move
                        as well as do something else, though a full
                        sprint will take up the entire round.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        If a character is performing an attack, then
                        any special attacks must be declared at this
                        point, before initiative is determined.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        Action determination is considered to be
                        simultaneous for everyone. If a character
                        wishes to 'wait' then they must declare what
                        they are waiting for, and what they will do
                        when it happens. Declarations such as
                        <e>I'll hit him if he moves</e>
                        are perfectly valid.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        It is not possible to wait until the end of
                        the round - any waiting must be for a particular
                        event. It is not possible to wait for a non
                        event. For example, an archer might specify
                        that they are waiting for someone to come
                        through a door, and that they will shoot them
                        when they do. If someone comes through the door,
                        then they get an attack, otherwise they perform
                        no action that round.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        Further, a declaration to shoot someone if they
                        come through the door, otherwise shoot someone
                        else is not valid. The character will not know
                        that someone is not going to come through the
                        door until the round has ended, by which time
                        it is too late.
                    </para>

                    <sect4>
                        <title>Declaring Attacks</title>

                        <para>
                            Only one attack may be declared each round
                            by a character. The target of the attack
                            must be specified, as well as whether the
                            attack is a special attack of any kind.
                            Many characters may attack a single target
                            however, up to whatever is practical given
                            the size of the target. Assume that four
                            people can attack a man sized target, unless
                            circumstances dictate otherwise.
                        </para>

                        <para>
                            If attackers are armed with long weapons
                            such as spears, then up to six may attack
                            at once.
                        </para>
                    </sect4>

                    <sect4>
                        <title>Declaring Defences</title>

                        <para>
                            A character may defend against any number
                            of opponents, though there are penalties
                            if more than one defence is performed.
                            Since defences are being declared, it is
                            necessary for a character to know who is
                            attacking them that round.
                        </para>
                    </sect4>
                </sect3>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Initiative</title>

                    <para>
                        Initiative determines who acts first, with
                        higher initiatives going before lower ones.
                        If the character is making an attack, then
                        their initiative depends on their initiative
                        derived from their weapon statistic. Most other
                        actions can be derived from their brawling
                        initiative (agility x brawl).
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        Some actions are considered to be either slow or
                        fast. Fast actions always come before other
                        actions, and slow actions always go after all
                        other actions. When resolving initiative, resolve
                        all fast actions first, then all normal actions,
                        then all slow actions. In a few circumstances,
                        an action may be very slow, in which case these
                        are resolved last. Use of some special attacks
                        will make an action slow or fast.
                    </para>
                    
                    <example>
                        <para>
                            Alice has an initiative of 28, Bob has an
                            initiative of 24 and Charles has an initiative
                            of 22. Alice and Bob make normal attacks, but
                            Charles makes an aggressive attack, which is
                            always fast. When actions are resolved, fast
                            actions go first, so Charles is first to act.
                            Next, normal actions are performed, so Alice
                            acts, followed by Bob.
                        </para>

                        <para>
                            If Alice's action was also an aggressive attack,
                            then she would be considered fast as well as
                            Charles. When fast actions are resolved, they
                            would be in order of Alice, then Charles. Bob
                            would then act last, taking only a normal speed
                            action.
                        </para>
                    </example>

                    <sect4>
                        <title>Fumbling initiative</title>
                        
                        <para>
                            If initiative is fumbled, by rolling a 1,
                            then two things occur. First, the character
                            acts in the next speed category down, so a
                            normal action becomes slow, and a slow action
                            becomes very slow.
                        </para>
                        
                        <para>
                            Secondly, the person becomes fatigued, gaining
                            one level of temporary fatigue.
                        </para>
                    </sect4>

                    <sect4>
                        <title>Reactions</title>

                        <para>
                            A reaction is in response to another's action.
                            Some special attack types are considered to
                            be reactions. In this case, the reacting
                            character acts immediately after the action
                            that they are reacting to.
                        </para>
                        
                        <para>
                            Normally, a reaction can only be used if the
                            character's action would normally occur before
                            the event. However, it is delayed until after
                            the event. A reaction can be carried over until
                            the next round.
                        </para>
                    </sect4>
                </sect3>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Perform Actions</title>

                    <para>
                        Actions are performed.
                    </para>
                </sect3>

                <sect3>
                    <title>End of Round</title>

                    <para>
                        At the end of each round, any general
                        bookkeeping can be performed. If stamina rolls
                        are needed to remain conscious, then they are
                        made now.
                    </para>
                </sect3>
            </sect2>

            <sect2>
                <title>Making an Attack</title>

                <para>
                    If a character chooses to make an attack on someone,
                    then the target can choose either to defend
                    themselves or not, though this decision must be made
                    when actions are declared.
                </para>

                <para>
                    The attacker makes an attack roll, using their
                    attack rating as follows.
                </para>

                <skillequation>
                    <attribute>attribute</attribute>
                    <skill>skill</skill>
                    <bonus>weapon attack bonus</bonus>
                    <die/>
                </skillequation>

                <para>
                    If the defender is not defending, then the target
                    difficulty is 15. If the defender is defending,
                    then they make a defence roll.
                </para>

                <para>
                    If the attack roll is equal to or greater than the
                    defense roll, then the attack was a success.
                </para>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Multiple Opponents</title>

                    <para>
                        A defender who is having to defend against
                        multiple opponents will be at a penalty to all
                        their defence rolls. It can sometimes be better
                        to not defend against all attacks, in order to
                        at least have a chance at defending against some
                        of them. It is not possible to defend against more
                        than four attacks in a round.
                    </para>


                    <table>
                        <title>Defending Against Multiple Opponents</title>

                        <colspec colwidth="3cm"/>
                        <colspec colwidth="2cm"/>
                        <colspec colwidth="2cm"/>
                        <thead>
