                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry>16-20</entry>
                            <entry>4</entry>
                            <entry>-6</entry>
                            <entry>Serious</entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry>21 - 25</entry>
                            <entry>5</entry>
                            <entry>-10</entry>
                            <entry>Critical</entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry>26 - 30</entry>
                            <entry>6</entry>
                            <entry>-15</entry>
                            <entry>Fatal</entry>
                        </row>
                    </tbody>
                </table>

                <para>
                    Each level of wound gives a penalty, as shown in the
                    <e>Penalties due to Wounds</e> table.
                    The penalty is to all actions performed by the character
                    while at that wound level.
                </para>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Critical Wounds</title>

                    <para>
                        If a character becomes critically wounded
                        (-10 penalty), then they must make an immediate
                        stamina x 4 roll at difficulty 20. Failure means
                        that they fall unconscious at the end of the round.
                        It may be assumed that civilians and
                        non-professional warriors either fall unconscious,
                        or retreat from battle when their wounds reach this
                        state.
                    </para>
                </sect3>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Fatal Wounds</title>

                    <para>
                        If a character becomes fatally wounded, then they
                        must immediately make a stamina roll at difficulty 20
                        or die (with a fumble chance of 3, fumbling resulting
                        in death). If they get a good success (succeed by 10
                        or more), then they may continue normally, otherwise
                        they fall unconscious.
                    </para>

                    <sect4>
                        <title>Beyond Fatal</title>

                        <para>
                            If a character suffers damage that takes them
                            beyond <e>fatally wounded</e>,
                            then they are considered to be at fatal, but
                            the initial stamina difficulty is raised by 5
                            for each wound level beyond fatal they were
                            taken. For example, if someone is seriously
                            wounded, and suffers four extra wound levels,
                            they will become fatally wounded, and need
                            to make a stamina roll at difficulty 30 to
                            remain alive, and 40 to remain conscious.
                        </para>

                        <para>
                            The fumble chance is raised by 1 for each
                            wound beyond fatal that they are taken.
                        </para>

                        <para>
                            Damage such as this only affects the initial
                            stamina roll, and does not affect further
                            rolls to remain conscious and alive later on.
                            For all other purposes, there are no shades
                            of fatal wounds.
                        </para>
                    </sect4>

                    <sect4><title>Surviving Fatal wounds</title>
                        <para>
                            Unless they receive suitable medical attention,
                            a fatally wounded character will die eventually.
                            If the character is still conscious, they
                            must make another stamina roll at the end of
                            each round at a target difficulty of 30 to
                            remain conscious. Again, if the roll
                            fails by 10 or more, then the character dies.
                        </para>

                        <para>
                            An unconscious character must make a difficulty
                            20 roll each minute in order to remain alive.
                            Failure means death. A roll must be made
                            until the character receives first aid which
                            stabalises their condition.
                        </para>
                    </sect4>
                </sect3>
            </sect2>


            <sect2>
                <title>Stuns</title>

                <para>
                    Unlike wounds, stuns are short term and generally
                    non-fatal. Stun damage is caused by attacks which
                    bruise or scratch such as fists, chair legs and
                    staffs. It is possible to kill someone with stun
                    damage, though it is unlikely.
                </para>

                <para>
                    Unlike wounds, stun damage is not cumulative. If a
                    character receives a number of stuns greater than
                    the stun levels they currently have, then they become
                    stunned to that level. The stuns are not added to
                    the stuns they already have.
                </para>

                <para>
                    If a character receives at least one or more stuns
                    which do not exceed their current stun level, then
                    they gain one stun.
                </para>

                <para>
                    Similar to wounds, a character suffers penalties
                    from being stunned. The penalties are on a similar
                    scale for wound penalties, and a character who is
                    both wounded and stunned suffers both sets of
                    penalties.
                </para>

                <table>
                    <title>Penalties due to Stuns</title>
                    <colspec colwidth="2cm"/>
                    <colspec colwidth="1.5cm"/>
                    <colspec colwidth="1.5cm"/>
                    <colspec colwidth="3cm"/>
                    <thead>
                        <row>
                            <entry>Damage</entry>
                            <entry>Stuns</entry>
                            <entry>Penalty</entry>
                            <entry>Description</entry>
                        </row>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <row>
                            <entry>1 - 5</entry>
                            <entry>1</entry>
                            <entry>+0</entry>
                            <entry>Bruised</entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry>6 - 10</entry>
                            <entry>2</entry>
                            <entry>-1</entry>
                            <entry>Dazed</entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry>11 - 15</entry>
                            <entry>3</entry>
                            <entry>-3</entry>
                            <entry>Bloodied</entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry>16-20</entry>
                            <entry>4</entry>
                            <entry>-6</entry>
                            <entry>Battered</entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry>21 - 25</entry>
                            <entry>5</entry>
                            <entry>-10</entry>
                            <entry>Beaten</entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry>26 - 30</entry>
                            <entry>6</entry>
                            <entry>-15</entry>
                            <entry>Oblivious</entry>
                        </row>
                    </tbody>
                </table>

                <para>
                    Once a character becomes <e>oblivious</e>,
                    they must make a stamina roll of difficulty 30 or fall
                    unconscious. Every stun they receive after this
                    requires another stamina roll, plus the character
                    suffers a single wound.
                </para>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Excess stun damage</title>

                    <para>
                        If the number of stuns suffered in a single attack
                        takes the character beyond the
                        <e>oblivious</e> threshold, then
                        the excess stuns become wounds, and add to the
                        character's current wound total.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        A stamina roll is also required in order to
                        remain conscious. The target difficulty is
                        increased by 5 for each excess stun.
                    </para>
                </sect3>
            </sect2>

            <sect2>
                <title>Mixed damage</title>

                <para>
                    Some weapons have a damage type of
                    <e>Mixed</e>, which causes both stun and
                    wound damage. On a scale of severity, it isn't as deadly
                    as wound damage, but is worse than stun damage.
                </para>

                <para>
                    Mixed damage is split equally between stuns and wounds,
                    with any remainder going on stuns (so one level of
                    mixed damage is equivalent to a single stun).
                </para>

                <para>
                    All stuns from mixed damage are cumulative. If a
                    character receives three levels of mixed damage, he
                    suffers two stuns and one wound. If that character
                    already has two stuns and two wounds, he will now
                    have four stuns and three wounds.
                </para>
            </sect2>

            <sect2>
                <title>Fatigue</title>

                <para>
                    Fatigue is not strictly damage, but it is treated
                    in much the same way as damage is, so is described
                    here. Fatigue is gained due to strenuous exercise,
                    some mental/magical attacks or lack of sleep. Depending
                    on the magic system used, spell casting can also result
                    in fatigue being gained.
                </para>

                <para>
                    As for other types of <e>damage</e>,
                    fatigue is measured in levels, each level giving a
                    penalty to all actions. These levels range from 'OK'
                    to 'Exhausted'.
                </para>

                <para>
                    There are types of fatigue - temporary and permanent.
                    Unless stated otherwise, all fatigue gained is temporary
                    and can be lost with a short rest.
                </para>

                <para>
                    All fatigue is recorded on the same track. If a person
                    has two points of temporary fatigue and two points of
                    permanent fatigue, then for purposes of everything save
                    for recovery, they have four points of fatigue. For
                    someone with a stamina of 3, this would give them a
                    single -6 penalty, not two -1 penalties.
                </para>

                <para>
                    It is suggested that fatigue is kept track of on the
                    character sheet by crossing off temporary fatigue levels
                    with a single line, and permanent fatigue with a cross.
                </para>
            </sect2>
        </sect1>


        <sect1>
            <title>Armour</title>

            <para>
                The purpose of armour is to keep someone alive by absorbing
                or deflecting the force of a blow away from them. In reality,
                the relationship between weapons and armour is complicated,
                having evolved during an arms race lasting several millennia.
                As a type of armour was developed to counter the weapons
                then in use, so the weapons changed to minimise the effects
                of the new armour.
            </para>

            <para>
                Realistically, it is not always possible to say that one
                type of armour is better at stopping damage than another
                type. The usefulness of armour depends on whether the
                attack crushes, slices or pierces, and there are
                complications within these as well. Yags however,
                deliberately ignores this. Armour has a single
                protection value which works equally against all types
                of armour.
            </para>

            <para>
                A further simplification is that there are no hit locations.
                The protection value of armour also takes into account how
                much of the body it covers. It is left to GMs to rule when
                an attack can avoid armour - generally this will only be
                possible against an unsuspecting foe.
            </para>

            <sect2>
                <title>Choosing armour</title>

                <para>
                    A full set of armour can consist of several parts, and a
                    character can mix and match according to preference and
                    finances. Generally, armour cannot be layered - it is 
                    not possible to wear two chain hauberks at the same time.
                </para>

                <para>
                    Each item of armour has a protection value, and a load.
                    The total load and protection of all worn items is
                    totalled to give the final value. So, a character
                    wearing soft leather trousers (with a protection of 2)
                    and a soft leather jacket (also 2), would have
                    a total armour protection of 4.
                </para>

                <termlist>
                    <entry term="Jacket">
                        Covers the torso, arms and upper thighs.
                    </entry>

                    <entry term="Vest">
                        Covers the torso and shouldres.
                    </entry>

                    <entry term="Trousers">
                        Covers the legs and lower abdomen.
                    </entry>

                    <entry term="Helm">
                        Protects the head.
                    </entry>
        
                    <entry term="Hauberk">
                        A term used to describe a chainmail jacket. May
                        cover the legs down to the knees.
                    </entry>
                    
                    <entry term="Coif">
                        Covers the head, neck and shoulders. May be worn
                        under a helm.
                    </entry>

                    <entry term="Greaves">
                        Covers the legs. Values given are for a set of
                        greaves, one for each leg.
                    </entry>
                    
                    <entry term="Vambraces">
                        Protects the arms. As for greaves, values given
                        assume a set of vambraces.
                    </entry>
                </termlist>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Stacking Armour</title>

                    <para>
                        Normally, it is not possible to layer armour on top
                        of other armour - if it is managed, only the highest
                        protection value is applied. However, some types of
                        armour are designed to layer, and in this case the 
                        protection values are added together.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        Soft leather armour can be worn underneath chain or
                        plate armour. Plate armour such as greaves, vambraces
                        and breastplates can be worn over chain armour. It 
                        is possible to wear plate over chain over leather.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        The other layering combination is that a helm can 
                        be worn over a chain mail coif.
                    </para>
                </sect3>
            </sect2>

            <sect2>
                <title>Advantages of Armour</title>

                <para>
                    The total protection of all armour worn adds to the soak
                    of the wearer.
                </para>
            </sect2>
        </sect1>


        <sect1>
            <title>Healing and First aid</title>

            <sect2>
                <title>First aid</title>

                <para>
                    After a character has become injured, it may be
                    necessary for first aid to be applied to the wounds
                    in order for them to heal. Fresh wounds need to be
                    stabilised, a process which requires another
                    character to make an intelligence x first aid roll
                    on the wounded character.
                </para>

                <para>
                    The base difficulty to successfully first aid a
                    character's stuns is zero. To tend to a character's
                    wounds, the base difficulty is 10. In both cases, the
                    difficulty is modified upwards by the character's
                    total stun and wound penalties.
                </para>

                <para>
                    For example, a battered (-6) and lightly wounded (-1)
                    character would be difficulty 7 to first aid their
                    stuns, and 17 to first aid their wounds.
                </para>

                <para>
                    A character may first aid themselves - as long as they
                    are conscious - but they suffer all their wound
                    penalties to their skill roll (as well as them adding
                    to the difficulty of the task).
                </para>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Tending to Stuns</title>

                    <para>
                        A successful first aid attempt against stuns will
                        heal one level of stun immediately, plus a further
                        level for every full 10 points the healer rolled
                        above the difficulty.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        Stuns do not need to be stabalised, so there is no
                        penalty from failing to have first aid performed as
                        long as the character is only stunned.
                    </para>
                </sect3>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Tending to Wounds</title>

                    <para>
                        A successful first aid attempt against wounds will
                        stabalise the wound, preventing it from becoming
                        infected or worsening. If the roll was at least 10
                        points higher than the difficulty, then a single
                        wound level is immediately healed.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        A character who is fatally wounded, does not have
                        to roll to see if they die while the first aid
                        attempt is in progress. However, if the first aid
                        fails (at the end of the minute it takes), then
                        the character has to start rolling again as per
                        normal.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        If a wound is not successfully first aided within
                        an hour, then there is a chance that it becomes
                        infected and worsens. The character makes a stamina
                        roll at difficulty 20, modified by wound penalties.
                        Failure means that the wound is infected, and
                        worsens by one level. Each day thereafter, until
                        first aid is successfully attempted, another roll
                        is needed, with each failure worsening the wound
                        each time.
                    </para>
                </sect3>
            </sect2>

            <sect2>
                <title>Natural healing</title>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Recovering from stuns</title>

                    <para>
                        Stuns are healed after a night's rest. Each morning,
                        the character makes a stamina roll at difficulty 10,
                        modified by their current wound and stun penalties.
                        Success means that one stun level is healed, and each
                        10 above the difficulty heals a further stun level.
                    </para>
                </sect3>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Recovering from wounds</title>

                    <para>
                        Wounds heal naturally after a week. Each week, the
                        character gets a stamina roll at difficulty 20,
                        modified by their total stun and wound penalties.
                        On a success, a single level of wound is healed.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        A more seriously wounded character gets a recovery
                        roll at the end of each week. The difficulty
                        depends on the severity of the injury.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        If the character fumbles their stamina roll, then
                        their injury worsens, and they gain an extra wound
                        level. A character who is already fatally wounded
                        will die.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        It is not actually possible for a person with
                        average or worse stamina to recover from being
                        fatally wounded alone. Someone with the first aid
                        skill can grant a bonus if they spend time
                        looking after the wounded person. An intelligence
                        x first aid skill roll is made, and a bonus of
                        +1 per full 5 rolled is added to the patient's
                        stamina roll.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        A patient can look after themselves, though they
                        suffer wound and stun penalties to do so.
                    </para>
                </sect3>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Recovering from Fatigue</title>

                    <para>
                        The only way to recover from fatigue is through
                        rest. Temporary fatigue can be recovered in a
                        matter of minutes, whilst permanent fatigue can
                        only be recovered with a good sleep.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        For each level of fatigue a person has, it takes
                        five minutes to recover one temporary level. If a
                        person has four levels of temporary fatigue, then
                        it takes 20 minutes of rest to loose the first level,
                        then 15 minutes for the next level, 10 minutes for
                        the third level and finally 5 minutes for the last
                        level.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        Permanent fatigue counts towards temporary fatigue,
                        but can not be lost through simple rest. A person
                        with two permanent fatigue and two temporary, could
                        loose the temporary fatigue after 35 minutes, but
                        would need a night of rest to loose the rest.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        Permanent fatigue is recovered after a night of
                        rest. Four hours of sleep will remove all temporary
                        fatigue automatically, and one point of permanent
                        fatigue for every two points of stamina (rounded up).
                    </para>
                </sect3>
            </sect2>
        </sect1>

        <sect1>
            <title>Missile Combat</title>

            <para>
                So far everything that has been covered has dealt with
                melee combat between antagonists who are in close combat.
                The rules for missile weapons are similar. Unless a
                difference is noted, assume that missile combat works
                the same way.
            </para>

            <sect2>
                <title>Ranged combat skills</title>

                <para>
                    As for melee combat, there are a number of different
                    styles which make use of a particular skill.
                </para>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Thrown weapons</title>

                    <para>
                        All characters have some ability with the
                        <e>Throw</e> talent, which is the
                        ranged equivalent of the <e>Brawl</e> skill.
                        Thrown spears, javelins,
                        bottles, slings and axes are covered under this
                        skill. This actually covers the majority of
                        missile combat.
                    </para>
                </sect3>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Bow</title>

                    <para>
                        The bow, including both the longbow and shortbow,
                        requires this skill. The bow can be quite a deadly
                        weapon in the hands of a skilled professional, but
                        can be difficult to use.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        Both longbows and shortbows are constructed for a
                        given strength of user. A bow's strength rating is
                        both the minimum and maximum strength. A stronger 
                        bowman cannot use their full strength when
                        using the weapon.
                    </para>
                    
                    <para>
                        Longbows have the advantage that a skilled longbowman
                        can manage a larger 'pull' then an unskilled one of
                        equivalent strength (due to long hours spent
                        exercising wrist and arm muscles). For every full
                        four points of skill a longbowman has, then they
                        get an effective +1 to their strength when using a
                        longbow.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        A single attack action consists of loading, aiming
                        and firing the bow. This is considered to be a
                        slow action. If the bow was already loaded in a
                        previous round, then an attack action occurs on
                        a normal initiative.
                    </para>
                </sect3>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Crossbow</title>

                    <para>
                        Crossbows have their own skill. They are easier
                        to use for the unskilled user, but don't have the
                        accuracy at long range compared with the long bow.
                    </para>
                    
                    <para>
                        Loading and firing a crossbow in a single round is
                        always considered to be slow. If it was loaded in
                        a previous round, then a shot may be made as a
                        normal action.
                    </para>
                    
                    <para>
                        Medium and heavy crossbows may take several rounds
                        to load. On ongoing task must be completed in order
                        to load the crossbow. An attack may be made in the
                        round that the crossbow was loaded.
                    </para>
                    
                    <para>
                        For medium crossbows, the difficulty is 15, for 
                        heavy crossbows the difficulty is 20. In each case,
                        a strength x 4 roll is required.
                    </para>
                </sect3>
            </sect2>

            <sect2>
                <title>Size of Target</title>

                <para>
                    As for melee combat, there is a base difficulty needed
                    to hit a target. Unlike in melee combat though, this is
                    modified by the range to the target, and environmental
                    factors such as wind and visibility.
                </para>

                <para>
                    For a human sized target, the base difficulty is 15, as
                    for melee combat. For smaller or larger targets, the
                    difficulty changes however.
                </para>

                <targetlist bold="true" targetFirst="false">
                    <targetLabel>Difficulty</targetLabel>
                    <valueLabel>Size of target</valueLabel>

                    <entry value="Diminutive" target="30">
                        Size 0, which is about 10cm in length.
                    </entry>

                    <entry value="Tiny" target="25">
                        Size 1, about 30cm in length. A small cat.
                    </entry>

                    <entry value="Small" target="20">
                        Sizes 2 - 3. Cats and dogs, 60cm to 90cm in length.
                    </entry>

                    <entry value="Medium" target="15">
                        Sizes 4 - 6, from 130cm to 210cm in length or height.
                    </entry>

                    <entry value="Large" target="10">
                        Sizes 7 - 10, from 2m to 5m in length. Includes
                        lions, horses and the like.
                    </entry>

                    <entry value="Huge" target="5">
                        Sizes 11 - 15, up to 10m in length. Elephants,
                        houses and the like.
                    </entry>

                    <entry value="Enormous" target="0">
                        Sizes 16 - 21, up to 16m in length. Dinosaurs.
                    </entry>

                    <entry value="Gigantic" target="-5">
                        Sizes 22 - 28, up to 23m in length. The largest
                        dinosaurs and whales are gigantic.
                    </entry>

                    <entry value="Colossal" target="-10">
                        Sizes 29 - 36, up to 31m in length.
                    </entry>

                    <entry value="Titanic" target="-15">
                        Sizes 37+. Anything larger.
                    </entry>
                </targetlist>

                <para>
                    The very largest creatures are very difficult to miss at
                    close ranges. Groups of smaller creatures also count as
                    being of a larger size.
                </para>
            </sect2>

            <sect2>
                <title>Missile Ranges</title>

                <para>
                    There are two range factors to take into account - the
                    <e>range increment</e> of the weapon, and the <e>range
                    category</e> it is being fired at.
                </para>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Range Increment</title>

                    <para>
                        The range increment is a measure of how accurate the
                        weapon is at range. It is given as a distance, and
                        each multiple of this distance gives a +5 modifier
                        to the target difficulty.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        A long bow has a range increment of 25m. Targets
                        less than 25m away have no modifier. Targets which
                        are 25m or further away have +5 to the difficulty,
                        50m or further have +10 etc.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        Shooting a long bow against a <e>Colossal</e> target
                        at 200m, would be difficulty 30 (-10 for size, + 40
                        for the range).
                    </para>
                </sect3>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Range Category</title>

                    <para>
                        The range category is either <e>short</e>,
                        <e>medium</e> or <e>long</e>. A weapon cannot hit
                        targets beyond long range. The range category
                        affects the performance of the weapon, though not
                        the difficulty to hit. In most cases, this is just
                        the damage the weapon does.
                    </para>

                    <targetlist>
                        <targetLabel>Damage</targetLabel>
                        <valueLabel>Range category</valueLabel>

                        <entry value="Short" target="+0"/>
                        <entry value="Medium" target="-5"/>
                        <entry value="Long" target="-10"/>
                    </targetlist>

                    <para>
                        Weapons such as bows, crossbows, hurled weapons and
                        slings must be aimed on a ballistic trajectory to
                        hit targets at medium or long range. Targets at
                        short range can be hit on a more or less flat
                        trajectory. So, for example, it is not possible to
                        fire at long range down a low corridor.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        At medium range, there must be ample height available
                        equal to one quarter the range. At long range, half
                        the range is needed in height. Firing a long bow at
                        a target 200m away, requires 100m of height, since
                        this is at long range.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        Because of the angle the short will come down at, it
                        is not possible to fire through narrow gaps, such as
                        a window or arrow slit at long range - the archer
                        can hit the window, but not someone behind the
                        window. At medium range, it is possible to hit
                        someone immediately behind a window or similar gap,
                        but it would not be possible to fire through a
                        window to hit someone on the other side of the room.
                    </para>
                </sect3>

            </sect2>

            <sect2>
                <title>Missile Attacks</title>

                <para>
                    If a character declares an attack with a missile
                    weapon, then they roll initiative as per melee combat,
                    and act in standard initiative order.
                </para>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Defending with a missile weapon</title>

                    <para>
                        One problem with missile weapons is that it is not
                        possible to parry with them. If the weapon has an
                        equivalent melee defence total, then use the defence
                        total for that (i.e. a thrown dagger is treated as
                        a melee dagger for defence), otherwise it
                        is not possible to parry with a missile weapon.
                        Instead, the character must perform a brawling
                        defence (agility x brawl), with no modifier for
                        the weapon being used.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        Once a thrown weapon has been thrown, any defence
                        bonuses are lost.
                    </para>
                </sect3>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Defending against missile attacks</title>

                    <para>
                        Missile attacks can be dodged, but not parried
                        unless the defender has a shield, in which case
                        they get the defence bonus of the shield, but not
                        of any other weapon they are using.
                    </para>
                </sect3>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Firing into melee</title>

                    <para>
                        Firing into a melee combat is rarely a good idea,
                        but sometimes it is done anyway. If the target of
                        a missile attack is in close combat with anyone
                        else, then the fumble chance of the attack is
                        increased by two for each extra person. Firing
                        into a melee involving six people, would give a +10
                        to the fumble chance, meaning the attacker has a
                        chance of hitting the wrong target if the d20 rolls
                        less than 12.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        The chance of fumbling can be modified if the
                        target is much larger or smaller than the
                        obstructions. This is left for the GM to
                        decide, but if two humans are fighting a 20m
                        long dragon, then it is suggested that no
                        penalty is applied.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        A fumble in this situation means that a random
                        target is hit. It is possible to hit the 'right'
                        random target. Chance of hitting each target
                        should be based on size, and ideally distance from
                        the intended target. In reality, just assigning
                        equal chance to everyone is good enough.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        If someone is wrestling with the intended target,
                        add +5 to +15 to the fumble chance, depending on
                        how bad a shot it is. In all cases, a luck point
                        can be spent before hand to negate, or at
                        least reduce, the chance of hitting a friend.
                    </para>
                </sect3>
            </sect2>
        </sect1>

        <sect1>
            <title>Advanced Combat</title>

            <sect2>
                <title>Special Attacks</title>

                <para>
                    Instead of making a normal attack, before initiative
                    is determined, a character can opt to make one special
                    attack. Unless noted otherwise, these are available to
                    all forms of attack, and all types of weapons. In some
                    cases, special attacks can be combined, but only if it
                    is specifically noted.
                </para>

                <para>
                    If two actions are combined, and both modify the
                    initiative, then the slowest initiative is used. For
                    example, aiming allows a fast attack the following
                    round, and can be combined with killing blow, which
                    is a slow attack. A round is spent aiming, then the
                    following round a slow killing blow attack is made.
                </para>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Aggressive</title>

                    <para>
                        An all out melee attack is made, giving a +5 bonus
                        to attack and damage rolls, but a -10 to defence.
                        This attack is considered to be fast.
                    </para>
                </sect3>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Aimed Shot</title>

                    <para>
                        Only applicable for missile attacks. If an entire
                        round is spent aiming, then +1 is added to the
                        attacker's perception for the attack, which
                        occurs as a fast attack the following round. This
                        attack may be combined with killing blows or
                        ambush actions.
                    </para>
                </sect3>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Ambush</title>

                    <para>
                        If the target is unaware of the attack, then an
                        ambush may be performed. This grants no bonuses
                        to the attack, but the total soak of the target
                        is halved. Furthermore, the attack counts
                        as a <e>killing blow</e>. An
                        ambusher cannot defend during the round, and
                        such an attack is always considered to be slow.
                    </para>
                </sect3>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Cleaving Attack</title>

                    <para>
                        A cleaving attack is always slow, and also gives
                        a -10 penalty to the attack roll, or -5 if a two
                        handed weapon is being used. If the attack is
                        successful, the armour (not soak) of the target
                        is halved. Such an attack can only be performed
                        in melee.
                    </para>
                </sect3>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Defensive</title>

                    <para>
                        If the round is spent fighting defensively, then
                        a +5 bonus to defence rolls is gained, and a -10
                        penalty to attack rolls. Any attacks made are slow,
                        and only melee actions can be performed.
                    </para>
                </sect3>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Disarm</title>

                    <para>
                        This is a melee attack, which can be perform with
                        a melee weapon against a melee weapon. It cannot
                        be used against shields, and suffers -10 against
                        a weapon which is being used two handed. A weapon
                        attack roll is made at -10, versus the defence
                        roll as per normal (though no defence penalty is
                        suffered from fighting multiple opponents for this
                        roll only). On success, the defender is off
                        balance and looses attack and defence bonuses
                        from that weapon for the rest of the round (it is
                        possible that this has no effect). A second
                        oppossed roll is made, with the dexterity of the
                        attack and defender. If the attack equals or
                        exceeds the defender, then the defender has been
                        disarmed.
                    </para>
                </sect3>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Feint</title>

                    <para>
                        No attack is made this turn (but character can
                        defend as normal), and a +5 bonus to attack and
                        initiative is gained next turn, as long as the
                        same opponent is being fought. Only possible in
                        melee, and during the following round, any other
                        special attack can be used. Further, special
                        attacks which automatically go last,
                        instead act at normal initiative.
                    </para>
                </sect3>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Killing blow</title>

                    <para>
                        A killing blow is a slow attack, and the character
                        suffers a -10 penalty to the attack roll. If the
                        attack is successful, and at least two full
                        categories of damage are caused, the target is
                        instantly killed. If performed with a weapon doing
                        stun or mixed damage, the target is knocked out
                        instead.
                    </para>
                </sect3>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Subduing Attack</title>

                    <para>
                        Any attack with a melee weapon can be turned into
                        a subduing attack, causing stun damage instead of
                        wounds or mixed damage.
                    </para>
                </sect3>

            </sect2>

            <sect2>
                <title>Counter strikes</title>

                <para>
                    Counter strikes are secondary attacks made against
                    an attacker as part of a defence. They represent
                    punches, kicks, shield bashes and similar actions
                    that occur as part of a melee - effectively 'dirty
                    fighting'.
                </para>

                <para>
                    A counter strike is a free action that does not need
                    to be declared before hand. However, two requirements
                    must be met in order for a counter strike to be made.
                    The first is that the character must have already
                    acted this round (i.e. it must be after their
                    initiative), and secondly, they must have made a
                    successful defence against an attacker by at least
                    ten points. If these two requirements have been met,
                    then a counter strike may be made against the
                    attacker (for a counter strike, the strike is made
                    by the defender against the attacker).
                </para>

                <para>
                    The defender (the character making the counter strike)
                    makes a brawling attack, with penalties equal to those
                    they had for the defence roll (including those for
                    defending against multiple opponents). The attacker
                    makes a brawl defence roll, and if he succeeds, then
                    the counter strike fails. Note that the brawl defence
                    suffers penalties for performing multiple defences,
                    i.e. if the attacker was already defending against two
                    people, then his defence would be at -10. The brawl
                    defence is considered a 'free' defence, but does suffer
                    the penalties for other defences.
                </para>

                <para>
                    A successful counter strike results in a brawling
                    (stun) damage roll. The counter striker may use the
                    damage bonus of their weapon or shield (depending on
                    where the initial attack came from), though the
                    damage is always considered to be stun damage.
                </para>

                <para>
                    If the counter striker is attacking aggresively,
                    or is in a berserk rage, or performing any similar
                    action which gives a penalty to defence rolls, then
                    this penalty does not apply to the counter strike.
                    However, the attack bonus is not gained for the
                    counter strike attack either.
                </para>
            </sect2>

            <sect2>
                <title>Berserkers</title>

                <para>
                    Berserkers are mad warriors who show little concern
                    for their own survival. Fueled up on bloodlust,
                    religious fervour or drugs, they are able to shrug
                    aside injuries, and fight with a strength and
                    ferocity not normally possible.
                </para>

                <para>
                    Being a berserker is considered an advantage,
                    and only characters who have purchased it at
                    character generation may go berserk.
                </para>

                <sect3>
                    <title>The berserker advantage</title>

                    <para>
                        The advantage is purchased to a level, from one
                        upwards. Normally six is the maximum, though higher
                        levels may be possible through divine inspiration
                        or magic.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        If may be possible to increase the level of this
                        advantage over time, though it may not be improved
                        with experience. Being a berserker is a mind set
                        which is difficult to learn.
                    </para>
                </sect3>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Going berserk</title>

                    <para>
                        Going berserk is relatively easy, as long as there
                        is a reason to fight. No roll is necessary - if there
                        is a fight at hand, and the character wants to go 
                        berserk, then they can do, and they gain all the 
                        bonuses thereof.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        If there is no-one to fight, then entering a berserk
                        rage is not possible. There must be the promise of 
                        blood letting in the very near future.
                    </para>

                    <sect4>
                        <title>Not going berserk</title>

                        <para>
                            If a berserker gets involved in a fight in which
                            they do not want to go berserk, then a will check 
                            is required in order to restrain themselves.
                            Failure means that they go berserk, getting any
                            bonuses and penalties associated with that.
                        </para>

                        <para>
                            The difficulty to avoid going berserk is based on
                            the size of the fight. The bigger and more heroic
                            the fight, the harder it is to resist going
                            berserk. The character rolls will x 4, at a
                            penalty of 5 x berserker level.
                        </para>

                        <targetlist targetFirst="true" bold="true">
                            <title>Resisting Going Berserk</title>

                            <targetLabel>Target</targetLabel>
                            <valueLabel>Situation</valueLabel>

                            <entry target="0" value="Friendly">
                                A small, friendly fight.
                            </entry>

                            <entry target="5" value="Inferior foe">
                                The foe is obviously inferior, and easy
                                to defeat.
                            </entry>

                            <entry target="10" value="Mildly inferior">
                                The foe is relatively easy to beat.
                            </entry>

                            <entry target="15" value="Similar">
                                Foe is a challenge.
                            </entry>

                            <entry target="20" value="Superior">
                                Foe is superier.
                            </entry>

                            <entry target="25" value="Greatly superior">
                                Foe is greatly superior.
                            </entry>
                        </targetlist>

                        <para>
                            Whether a foe is inferior or superior, depends
                            on the skill of the foe, as well as numerical
                            superiority.
                        </para>
                    </sect4>
                </sect3>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Effects of berserk combat</title>

                    <para>
                        A berserk warrior must fight the nearest foe to
                        them, and may never use missile weapons. If 
                        there is not a foe in range, then they must
                        close with the enemy as quickly as possible. 
                        A berserker may never fight defensively.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        The level of the berserker advantage adds to the
                        attack, initiative and damage rolls of the 
                        berserker. It also subtracts from the
                        berserker's defence rolls.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        Any wound, stun or fatigue penalties are reduced
                        by the level of the advantage. Rolls to stay 
                        alive and conscious get a bonus equal
                        to the advantage.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        Finally, a berserker gets extra wound and stun
                        levels. These are temporary and are lost at the
                        end of the battle. One extra wound and stun level
                        is gained per two full levels of advantage. The
                        first level is an extra hurt and bruised
                        level. The second is an extra light
                        and dazed level. The third is an extra
                        medium and bloodied level.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        The real level is lost first when the character is
                        injured, and the temporary level is lost second.
                        At the end of the fight, the temporary levels go 
                        away, as do any wounds or stuns in them.
                    </para>
                </sect3>

            </sect2>

            <sect2>
                <title>Mounted combat</title>

                <para>
                    Fighting from horse back can be tricky, but for a
                    skilled rider it can be a big advantage. If the rider
                    has a riding skill less than four, then an agility 
                    based riding check is required whenever an
                    attack is made, against a target of 15. A rider
                    with a skill of four or more does not have to make 
                    this roll.
                </para>

                <para>
                    Failure of the riding roll means that the character
                    becomes unstable, and must make a second roll at the
                    same difficulty to remain on the horse. If the rider
                    is not using saddle and stirrups, then both
                    difficulties are increased by 5.
                </para>

                <para>
                    The character's ride skill adds to all initiative,
                    attack, defence and damage rolls made while on 
                    horseback. For example, a rider with a skill of 5,
                    gets +5 to all these rolls. No other bonuses due to
                    being on higher ground etc are gained. The bonuses 
                    do apply when fighting another mounted warrior.
                </para>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Mounted charge</title>

                    <para>
                        A <e>mounted charge</e> is a special kind of attack
                        that uses a lance from horseback, and can only be
                        used after at least a full round of charging. This
                        can only be done from a trained warhorse.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        On a successful mounted attack, damage is done with
                        a bonus equal to the strength of the mount (on top
                        of any bonuses due to the <e>ride</e> skill).
                        Furthermore, for each wound dealt, a stun is dealt
                        as well from the shock of the attack.
                    </para>
                </sect3>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Overbear</title>

                    <para>
                        A warhorse can be made to attack an opponent,
                        knocking them back or to the ground.
                    </para>
                </sect3>
            </sect2>

            <sect2>
                <title>Poison</title>

                <para>
                    Use of poison is often frowned upon by honourable
                    warriors, but not everyone is honourable, and not
                    everyone is a warrior willing to stand up in a
                    toe-to-toe fight. Poison may be used on darts, put
                    in food, or put on bladed weapons. Different types
                    of poisons have varying effectiveness, though very
                    few will give instant death.
                </para>

                <para>
                    For a full discussion on the use of poisons, see
                    Herb Lore. However, some simple poison rules are
                    given here.
                </para>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Resisting Poison</title>

                    <para>
                        Any poison may be resisted by making a resistence
                        roll. This is normally stamina x size of the
                        intended victim.
                    </para>
                </sect3>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Effects of Poison</title>

                    <para>
                        Poison can take a varying amount of time to take
                        affect. This may be a round, a minute, 15 minutes,
                        a day or any other period of time. When a poison is
                        first administered, a resistence roll is not made,
                        instead the roll is made after the given period of
                        time has passed. Even deadly poisons will tend to
                        have times in the minutes.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        The target difficulty of the resistence roll is the
                        strength of the poison. A good poison will tend to
                        have a strength in the 30 - 50 range. Whether the
                        resistence roll was successful or not, the poison
                        will continue to do damage to the victim. Once the
                        poison's effect time has passed again, then another
                        resistence roll is required, at a reduced difficulty.
                        Normally, the difficulty drops by 5 each time,
                        though this will be specified in the poison
                        description.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        For example, a poison with a strength of 40, and a
                        time of 1 minute, would require a resistence roll
                        against 40 after one minute, against 35 after two
                        minutes, then 30 after three minutes etc. Once 0
                        or less has been reached, no further rolls are
                        required and the poison is considered to have
                        finished its work.
                    </para>

                    <sect4>
                        <title>When poison works</title>

                        <para>
                            If a resistence roll was successful, then the
                            poison has no effect over that time period. If
                            it failed however, then the victim suffers
                            some effect from the poison. Poisons will have
                            a number of effects listed, in increasing order
                            of severity. For example, these might be
                            nausea, weakness, cramps, paralysis, death.
                            </para>

                        <para>
                            The first time the resistence is failed, the
                            first effect takes affect. The next failure
                            causes the next effect and so on. For the
                            above example, for a poison of strength 40,
                            most people are likely to suffer nausea,
                            weakness and cramps. Many people may suffer
                            paralysis, and a few would actually die (in
                            worst case, a stamina x size roll of 20 would
                            need to be failed in order to die).
                        </para>
                    </sect4>

                </sect3>

            </sect2>
        </sect1>
